                <div class="plan-section">
                    <h3>ü•ó Dietary Recommendations</h3>
                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h4>General Nutrition Guidelines for Weight Loss</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Create a caloric deficit of 500-750 calories per day for safe weight loss (0.5-1 kg per week)</li>
                            <li>Focus on whole, unprocessed foods - vegetables, fruits, lean proteins, whole grains</li>
                            <li>Increase protein intake to 1.2-1.6g per kg body weight to preserve muscle mass</li>
                            <li>Stay hydrated - drink at least 8-10 glasses of water daily</li>
                            <li>Limit added sugars and refined carbohydrates</li>
                            <li>Include healthy fats from nuts, seeds, avocados, and olive oil</li>
                            <li>Practice portion control - use smaller plates and mindful eating</li>
                            <li>Eat regular meals - don't skip breakfast</li>
                            <li>Reduce sodium intake to less than 2,300mg per day</li>
                            <li>Include fiber-rich foods (25-30g daily) for satiety</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h4>Foods to Prioritize</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Leafy greens: spinach, kale, lettuce</li>
                            <li>Lean proteins: chicken breast, fish, tofu, legumes</li>
                            <li>Whole grains: brown rice, quinoa, oats</li>
                            <li>Low-fat dairy or alternatives</li>
                            <li>Fresh fruits (in moderation)</li>
                            <li>Non-starchy vegetables</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="info-card">
                        <h4>Foods to Limit or Avoid</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Sugary beverages and sodas</li>
                            <li>Fried and processed foods</li>
                            <li>White bread, pastries, and refined grains</li>
                            <li>High-fat dairy products</li>
                            <li>Processed meats</li>
                            <li>Excessive alcohol consumption</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Medicine Options -->
                <div class="plan-section">
                    <h3>üíä Medical Treatment Options</h3>
                    <p style="color: #666; margin-bottom: 20px;"><strong>Important:</strong> All medications must be prescribed and monitored by a healthcare professional. Pharmacotherapy should be combined with lifestyle modifications for optimal results.</p>
                    
                    <div class="info-card" style="background: #fff3cd; border-left: 4px solid #ffc107;">
                        <h4>Treatment Guidelines</h4>
                        <p><strong>Candidates for Drug Therapy:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>BMI ‚â•30 kg/m¬≤ (Obesity)</li>
                            <li>BMI 27-29.9 kg/m¬≤ with one or more weight-related comorbidities</li>
                            <li>Have not achieved 5% weight loss with lifestyle interventions alone after 3-6 months</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Treatment Goals:</strong> 5% weight loss is considered effective; medications are typically used long-term as obesity is a chronic condition</p>
                    </div>

                    <h4 style="color: #667eea; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 15px;">First-Line Medications (GLP-1 Based Therapies - Most Effective)</h4>
                    
                    <div class="medicine-options">
                        <div class="medicine-card" style="border-left: 4px solid #28a745;">
                            <h4>Tirzepatide (Zepbound) - PREFERRED FIRST-LINE</h4>
                            <p><strong>Type:</strong> Dual GIP/GLP-1 receptor agonist (Most effective agent available)</p>
                            <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Increases satiety, slows gastric emptying, improves glucose-dependent insulin secretion</p>
                            <p><strong>Indication:</strong> BMI ‚â•30 or BMI ‚â•27 with comorbidities; Also approved for moderate-to-severe obstructive sleep apnea</p>
                            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Injectable, once weekly. Start 2.5mg, increase to 5mg, up to maximum 15mg weekly</p>
                            <p><strong>Expected Weight Loss:</strong> 15-22.5% of body weight (highest efficacy)</p>
                            <p><strong>Additional Benefits:</strong> Improves sleep apnea, glycemic control, cardiovascular risk factors</p>
                            <p style="color: #28a745;"><strong>Clinical Note:</strong> Superior efficacy compared to all other agents in head-to-head trials</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="medicine-card" style="border-left: 4px solid #28a745;">
                            <h4>Semaglutide (Wegovy) - PREFERRED FIRST-LINE</h4>
                            <p><strong>Type:</strong> GLP-1 receptor agonist</p>
                            <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Reduces appetite, increases satiety, slows gastric emptying</p>
                            <p><strong>Indication:</strong> BMI ‚â•30 or BMI ‚â•27 with comorbidities; Also approved for cardiovascular risk reduction in patients with established CVD</p>
                            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Injectable, once weekly. Titrate from 0.25mg up to 2.4mg weekly over 16 weeks</p>
                            <p><strong>Expected Weight Loss:</strong> 10-15% of body weight</p>
                            <p><strong>Cardiovascular Benefits:</strong> Reduces major adverse cardiovascular events by 20% in patients with established CVD</p>
                            <p><strong>Additional Approvals:</strong> Treatment of MASH (metabolic-associated steatohepatitis) with liver fibrosis</p>
                            <p style="color: #28a745;"><strong>Preferred for:</strong> Patients with cardiovascular disease or at high CV risk</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="medicine-card" style="border-left: 4px solid #28a745;">
                            <h4>Liraglutide (Saxenda)</h4>
                            <p><strong>Type:</strong> GLP-1 receptor agonist (first approved GLP-1 for obesity)</p>
                            <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Appetite suppression, increases satiety</p>
                            <p><strong>Indication:</strong> BMI ‚â•30 or BMI ‚â•27 with weight-related conditions</p>
                            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Injectable, once daily. Titrate from 0.6mg to 3.0mg daily over 5 weeks</p>
                            <p><strong>Expected Weight Loss:</strong> 5-10% of body weight</p>
                            <p><strong>Clinical Note:</strong> Less effective than semaglutide and tirzepatide; daily injection required</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="info-card" style="background: #e7f3ff; border-left: 4px solid #2196F3; margin-top: 15px;">
                            <h4>GLP-1 Medication Important Information</h4>
                            <p><strong>Common Side Effects:</strong> Nausea (25-40%), vomiting, diarrhea, constipation (usually improve with time)</p>
                            <p><strong>Management Tips:</strong> Eat smaller meals, eat slowly, avoid high-fat/greasy foods, slower dose titration if needed</p>
                            <p><strong>Contraindications:</strong></p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Personal or family history of medullary thyroid cancer or MEN 2A/2B</li>
                                <li>Pregnancy or planning pregnancy</li>
                                <li>Severe gastroparesis or inflammatory bowel disease</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p><strong>Pre-Surgery:</strong> May need to be held before elective surgery due to delayed gastric emptying</p>
                            <p><strong>Long-term Use:</strong> Weight regain occurs if medication is stopped; typically used indefinitely</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h4 style="color: #667eea; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Second-Line Medications (Alternatives if GLP-1 not suitable)</h4>

                    <div class="medicine-options">
                        <div class="medicine-card" style="border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                            <h4>Phentermine-Topiramate (Qsymia)</h4>
                            <p><strong>Type:</strong> Combination appetite suppressant</p>
                            <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Phentermine (sympathomimetic) + Topiramate (anticonvulsant) - suppresses appetite, increases satiety</p>
                            <p><strong>Indication:</strong> BMI ‚â•30 or BMI ‚â•27 with comorbidities (without cardiovascular disease or uncontrolled hypertension)</p>
                            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Oral, once daily. Start 3.75/23mg, increase to 7.5/46mg, up to max 15/92mg</p>
                            <p><strong>Expected Weight Loss:</strong> 8-10% of body weight</p>
                            <p><strong>Additional Benefits:</strong> May help with migraine prevention (topiramate component)</p>
                            <p><strong>Important Warnings:</strong> Teratogenic - requires monthly pregnancy testing; avoid in cardiovascular disease</p>
                            <p><strong>Contraindications:</strong> Pregnancy, glaucoma, hyperthyroidism, uncontrolled hypertension, cardiovascular disease</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="medicine-card" style="border-left: 4px solid #ff9800;">
                            <h4>Naltrexone-Bupropion (Contrave)</h4>
                            <p><strong>Type:</strong> Combination opioid antagonist + antidepressant</p>
                            <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Affects brain reward pathways and appetite regulation through POMC neurons</p>
                            <p><strong>Indication:</strong> BMI ‚â•30 or BMI ‚â•27 with comorbidities</p>
                            <p><strong>Dosage:</strong> Oral, twice daily. Titrate from 1 tablet daily to 2 tablets twice daily over 4 weeks</p>
                            <p><strong>Expected Weight Loss:</strong> 4-6% of body weight</p>
                            <p><strong>Potential Benefits:</strong> May help with depression, smoking cessation, alcohol use disorder</p>
                            <p><strong>Side Effects:</strong> Nausea (30%), headache, constipation, insomnia; monitor for depression/suicidal thoughts</p>
                            <p><strong>Contraindications:</strong> Seizure disorders, bulimia, chronic opioid use, u
